  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How much does it cost to buy a flight simulator?",
  "response": "The cost of buying a flight simulator can vary widely based on several factors, such as the level of realism, the type of aircraft you want to simulate, and whether you're looking for hardware, software, or both. Here are some general categories and their potential costs:\n\n1. **Home-based Software Simulators**: \n   - **Basic Software**: Popular programs like Microsoft Flight Simulator, X-Plane, and Prepar3D can range from $60 to $200, depending on the version and any additional DLC or expansions.\n   - **Add-ons**: These can include additional aircraft, scenery, airports, and other enhancements. Costs can range from $10 to $100 or more per add-on.\n\n2. **Flight Simulator Hardware**:\n   - **Basic Equipment**: Includes items like a yoke, joystick, rudder pedals, and throttle quadrant. High-quality options can cost from $100 to $1,000 for a complete set.\n   - **Advanced Equipment**: This can include instrument panels, realistic cockpit setups, and high-resolution monitors or VR headsets. Prices can range from $1,000 to well over $10,000.\n\n3. **Commercial-grade Simulators**: \n   - These are used by flight schools and pilot training programs and can cost from $50,000 to several million dollars, depending on their sophistication and capabilities.\n\n4. **DIY Setups**: \n   - Building your own home cockpit can vary greatly in cost, starting from a few hundred dollars for a basic setup to tens of thousands for a highly realistic cockpit.\n\n5. **Professional/ Commercial Simulators**:\n   - Full-motion simulators used by airlines for pilot training can cost anywhere from $1 million to $30 million or more.\n\nWhen considering purchasing a flight simulator, it's essential to determine your budget, what you want to use it for (e.g., hobbyist flying, training, etc.), and how realistic and immersive you want the experience to be.",
